<header>
  <h1>Tables</h1>
</header>

<section id="introduction">
	<p class="introduction">
		<strong>Tables</strong> shine when you need to present dense, comparable data—think schedules, price grids, inventories, and research results. Use them to reveal relationships across rows and columns, not to lay out a page; each column should have a clear heading, and every cell should align to a single idea so readers can scan without guesswork.
	</p>
	<p class="introduction">
		Structure tables semantically with headers, summaries, and predictable state styling so screen readers and keyboard users get the same clarity as sighted users. Pair responsive patterns—like horizontal scrolling, wrapping labels, or stacked layouts on small screens—with concise copy so the data stays legible across breakpoints.
	</p>
</section>

<section id="table-basic">
  <header>
    <h2>Basic tables</h2>
  </header>

